      <span class="mn">12</span>
     </div>
    </div>
    <span width="0.25em" class="mspace"/>
    <span class="mtext">F</span>
    <span stretchy="false" class="mo">/</span>
    <span class="mtext">m</span>
   </div>
  </div>) and amplitude of the electric field, respectively. A notable change takes place in absorbing medium where the real and imaginary parts of first and third-order susceptibilities interplay between them and accordingly modulate 
  <div class="inline-formula">
   <div id="M16" altimg="si5.svg" class="math">
    <div class="msub">
     <div class="mrow">
      <span class="mi">n</span>
     </div>
     <div class="mrow">
      <span class="mn">2</span>
     </div>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div> and 
  <div class="inline-formula">
   <div id="M17" altimg="si7.svg" class="math">
    <div class="msub">
     <div class="mrow">
      <span class="mi">α</span>
     </div>
     <div class="mrow">
      <span class="mn">2</span>
     </div>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div>. In consequence, the expressions of 
  <div class="inline-formula">
   <div id="M18" altimg="si5.svg" class="math">
    <div class="msub">
     <div class="mrow">
      <span class="mi">n</span>
     </div>
     <div class="mrow">
      <span class="mn">2</span>
     </div>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div> and 
  <div class="inline-formula">
   <div id="M19" altimg="si7.svg" class="math">
    <div class="msub">
     <div class="mrow">
      <span class="mi">α</span>
     </div>
     <div class="mrow">
      <span class="mn">2</span>
     </div>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div> are markedly altered (from that of non-absorbing one) and the aforesaid proportionality gets completely lost. It, therefore, appears important to measure the deviation in the magnitudes of 
